        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2059.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sarah Harriet Haliburton</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> 2: 243–4, CD argued that the antlers of female reindeer were of no use to them. Crotch had written to him suggesting that they were used by the pregnant females to drive off the males once the males had cleared snow from the grass with their forefeet (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8031.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. D. Crotch, 24 October 1871</ref>). CD cited Crotch’s further observations in this letter in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 503 (see also <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 20, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8632.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. D. Crotch, 17 November 1872</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Crotch published his findings on the lemmings, the product of ten consecutive summers spent in Norway, in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1671.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Crotch 1876</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD published on the homing instinct in animals in his letter ‘Perception in the lower animals’, <hi rend="italic">Nature</hi>, 13 March 1873, p. 360.</note>
        </div>        
            
